FOI Request LEX4335

Date: 2023

FOI Request Summary: Australian Electoral Commission's Engagement with Social Media Platforms

This Freedom of Information (FOI) request sought to understand the communication, referral, and content moderation processes between the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC), specifically its Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce (EIAT), and major social media platforms (Meta/Facebook/Instagram, Google/YouTube, TikTok, Twitter/X, Microsoft/LinkedIn). The focus was on ensuring electoral integrity, particularly concerning misinformation and disinformation related to the proposed Australian Referendum and recent by-elections.

Documents Released:

The released documents primarily consist of:
* Email correspondence between the AEC/EIAT and representatives from Meta, Google, TikTok, Twitter/X, and Microsoft.
* Formal notices and letters from the AEC to platforms, often relating to legislative updates or content referrals.
* Receipts acknowledging content removal or information requests.
* Meeting agendas for discussions between the AEC and platform representatives.
* Internal documents pertaining to platform escalation channels and training (mostly exempt).

Main Content of Documents:

The documents reveal extensive engagement focused on maintaining electoral integrity and combating misinformation:

  • Purpose of Engagement: The AEC actively collaborates with platforms to confirm and streamline processes for identifying, reporting, and potentially removing content that violates Australian electoral law or platform terms of service. This is particularly crucial for the upcoming Referendum, where the AEC's role is to address misinformation about the referendum process itself, rather than the 'Yes' or 'No' campaigns' content.

  • Platform-Specific Engagement:

    • Twitter/X: Documents include numerous "Content Removal Request" receipts, indicating active use of a referral system for issues like threats against AEC staff and electoral misinformation (e.g., claims of rigged votes or enrolment fraud). The AEC sought to confirm and re-establish secure legal referral pathways and discuss changes within the platform's operational environment.
    • Meta (Facebook/Instagram): Multiple emails show ongoing communication, often pertaining to content that could impact agency conduct or personal privacy. Referrals are subject to third-party review rights, suggesting sensitive content or operational details are involved.
    • Google/YouTube: Discussions centered on joining YouTube's "Trusted Flagger" program for faster content review, focusing on misinformation and hate speech. Google also informed the AEC about its decision to expand its political ads policy to include referendum advertising, requiring advertiser verification. Documents show the sharing of escalation pathways and reports on misinformation.
    • TikTok: Correspondence details the onboarding of the AEC to TikTok's "Safety Enforcement Tool (TSET)" for content takedown requests, confirming it as the preferred referral pathway. Discussions also covered data retention policies and legal notice procedures. TikTok committed to reviewing reported content, often within 24 hours.
    • Microsoft/LinkedIn: Engagements involved requesting and sharing information on common misinformation narratives and confirming appropriate email aliases for content referrals, especially for by-elections.

  • Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce (EIAT): The EIAT, chaired by the AEC, plays a central role in coordinating cross-government efforts and serves as the primary contact point for platforms on electoral integrity matters during events like the proposed Referendum and by-elections (e.g., Aston, Fadden).

  • Challenges and Exemptions: A significant number of documents are released in part or withheld entirely. Common exemption reasons include:

    • Personal privacy (Section 47F): Protecting individuals' identifying information.
    • Prejudice to investigations (Section 37(1)(a)): Protecting ongoing investigations into breaches of electoral law.
    • Substantial adverse effect on agency conduct (Section 47E(d)): Protecting operational methods or internal processes.
    • Business affairs (Section 47G(1)) / Commercial value (Section 47(1)): Protecting commercially sensitive information of the social media platforms.
    • Lawful methods or procedures (Section 37(2)(b)): Preventing disclosure of law enforcement or investigative techniques that could prejudice their effectiveness.

These exemptions indicate that while the general nature of collaboration is evident, specific details of content, investigations, and technical processes are often withheld to protect ongoing operations and sensitive commercial information.

AI Generated ?

As a left-leaning analyst, a review of these FOI documents from the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) reveals a complex interplay between government efforts to maintain democratic integrity and the growing influence of major tech corporations, raising both aligned and deviating points from progressive values, particularly concerning social justice, corporate power, and civil liberties.

Social Justice & Democratic Integrity:
The overarching theme is the AEC's proactive engagement with social media platforms (Twitter/X, Meta, TikTok, Google/YouTube, Microsoft) to combat "misinformation" and "disinformation" related to Australian electoral processes, including a proposed referendum (likely the Indigenous Voice to Parliament, as indicated by references to the "Constitution Alteration (Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Voice) 2023 Bill" in Documents 132 and 193). From a progressive standpoint, ensuring the integrity of democratic processes and fostering an informed citizenry is paramount for social justice, allowing all citizens to participate without undue influence or manipulation. The AEC's efforts to launch "early-education" campaigns and establish a "Referendum disinformation register" (Documents 132, 152, 193) are positive steps towards empowering voters with accurate information.

However, a critical lens is necessary. While the AEC clarifies it "does not have a role in fact-checking claims about the 'Yes' or 'No' campaigns for the referendum" and focuses solely on process-related misinformation, the practical application of this distinction can be blurry. The extensive redactions under "prejudice the conduct of an investigation of a breach, or possible breach, of the law" (Section 37(1)(a)) and "disclose lawful methods or procedures for preventing, detecting, investigating, or dealing with matters arising out of, breaches or evasions of the law" (Section 37(2)(b)) obscure the specific nature of the content being targeted and the criteria for its removal. This lack of transparency, even if intended to protect investigations, risks chilling legitimate public debate on a significant social justice issue.

Corporate Influence & Wealth Distribution:
The documents strongly highlight the extensive and deeply integrated relationship between the Australian government (via the AEC's Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce, EIAT) and powerful global tech corporations. The AEC is actively utilizing and requesting access to platforms' "referral pathways," "safety enforcement tools" (like TikTok's TSET), "legal portals," and "trusted flagger programs" (YouTube). This signifies a significant reliance on private entities to manage public information spaces essential for democratic functions.

The frequent use of "business affairs" (Section 47G(1)) and "information with commercial value" (Section 47(1)) exemptions, particularly for documents relating to TikTok and Twitter's internal systems (e.g., 169B, 169C), means that the proprietary methods and commercial interests of these immensely wealthy corporations are protected even when their operations directly impact a nation's democratic integrity. This arrangement points to a concerning power dynamic where government functions become intertwined with, and dependent on, corporate infrastructure, with limited public transparency into the terms or mechanisms of this collaboration. This deviates from progressive ideals that advocate for robust public oversight and regulation of concentrated private power, particularly when it influences fundamental democratic rights.

Civil Liberties (Freedom of Speech & Privacy):
This is perhaps the most contested area. While some interventions, such as those targeting content "inciting violence against AEC staff" (Document 171), are clearly justified and align with progressive values of safety and non-violence, the broader scope of "misinformation" control raises significant civil liberties concerns. The lack of granular detail in the released documents about what specific content (beyond generic titles like "Misinformation") is deemed problematic and why it necessitates removal by private platforms at government request, creates a "black box" around content moderation decisions.

The consistent application of privacy exemptions (Section 47F) is generally aligned with protecting individual privacy, which is a progressive value. However, the cumulative effect of privacy, business, and operational exemptions means that the public cannot fully scrutinize the extent to which official requests for "content removal" might inadvertently (or intentionally) suppress legitimate but inconvenient speech, or how the threshold for "misinformation" is determined and applied. This opacity risks eroding public trust and undermining the robust, open discourse that is vital for a healthy democracy, particularly when dealing with contentious national debates like a referendum.

In summary, the documents reveal a government agency appropriately focused on protecting the integrity of electoral processes. However, the extent of its reliance on, and the secrecy surrounding its collaboration with, powerful tech corporations for content moderation, coupled with broad exemptions, presents a potential deviation from progressive ideals of transparency, public accountability, and the protection of civil liberties in a free and open society.

The Freedom of Information (FOI) documents reveal extensive and active engagement by the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) with major social media platforms, including Twitter, Meta (Facebook/Instagram), TikTok, and Google/YouTube. The core of these interactions revolves around monitoring, requesting information about, and seeking the removal of online content, particularly concerning electoral processes and the proposed referendum. This deep level of government involvement in digital discourse presents several points of alignment and deviation from core conservative principles.

Individual Liberty and Limited Government: A Primary Concern

The documents raise significant alarms regarding individual liberty, particularly freedom of speech, and the principle of limited government. The sheer volume of "Content Removal Requests" and "Information Requests" to private platforms indicates a proactive government role in policing online speech. The AEC's establishment of the "Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce" (EIAT) and its participation in "Trusted Flagger" programs with platforms like YouTube position the government as an active participant in content moderation.

While the AEC states its focus is on "misinformation about the referendum process" and breaches of electoral law (e.g., Documents 152, 193), the repeated use of broad exemptions such as "prejudice the conduct of an investigation of a breach" (Section 37(1)(a)), "substantial adverse effect on proper and efficient conduct of an agency" (Section 47E(d)), and "disclose lawful methods or procedures for preventing, detecting, investigating, or dealing with... breaches" (Section 37(2)(b)) severely limits public scrutiny. This lack of transparency over what specific content is being targeted, or the methods used to identify it, creates a chilling effect on legitimate political expression and debate—a direct challenge to individual liberty.

The close collaboration between a government agency and private tech companies for content regulation blurs the lines of accountability. When government leverages the power of private platforms to achieve ends it might not be able to directly under existing law, it raises concerns about an end-run around constitutional protections and an unnecessary expansion of government influence into the private sphere. This suggests a deviation from the principle that government should be limited in its scope and not unduly interfere with the free flow of information, even if some of that information is deemed "misinformation."

Economic Efficiency and Fiscal Responsibility

While the documents do not detail specific monetary expenditures, the extensive coordination and resource allocation to the "Defending Democracy Unit," the EIAT, and direct engagement with multiple tech companies imply a considerable investment of taxpayer money and government personnel. For instance, the numerous emails discussing meeting schedules, "escalation pathways," and "onboarding" to platform-specific tools (e.g., TikTok's Safety Enforcement Tool) indicate ongoing administrative overhead.

From a fiscal conservative perspective, the question arises whether such an expansive and intrusive role in online content policing represents an efficient and responsible use of public funds. Exemptions citing "business affairs" (Section 47G(1)) or "information with commercial value" (Section 47(1)) for platform-specific tools further obscure the commercial arrangements and potential financial implications of these partnerships. An efficient, limited government should primarily focus on enforcing clear laws, not on extensive digital monitoring and content removal efforts that could be seen as a costly bureaucratic expansion into areas traditionally outside its purview.

National Security

The documents touch upon national security, primarily by mentioning "inciting violence against AEC staff" (e.g., Document 171). Addressing direct threats to public servants is a legitimate function of government and aligns with the national security principle. However, the frequent reference to "misinformation narratives" related to electoral processes (e.g., "misinformation about dominion voting machines," "multiple voting" in Document 171) suggests a broader interpretation of security. From a conservative viewpoint, conflating "misinformation" with national security threats risks weaponizing security concerns to suppress dissenting or critical voices, thereby expanding government power beyond protecting the nation from genuine external or violent internal threats.

In summary, while some actions aim to uphold electoral integrity, which is a necessary function of government, the documents reveal a concerning expansion of government into digital content control. This approach, characterized by active content flagging, opaque private sector partnerships, and broad interpretations of "misinformation," deviates significantly from conservative principles of individual liberty, limited government, economic efficiency, and restrained definitions of national security.

The FOI documents paint a disconcerting picture of an Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) actively engaged in extensive and opaque partnerships with major social media platforms (Meta, Twitter/X Corp., Google/YouTube, and TikTok) under the banner of "electoral integrity." Far from being a neutral administrative body, the AEC, primarily through its "Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce" (EIAT), appears to be systematically monitoring and influencing online discourse, with many of its operations shielded from public scrutiny.

Key Findings Highlighting Waste, Power Abuse, or Questionable Decision-Making:

  1. Systematic Content Control, Not Just Administration: The sheer volume of "Twitter Receipt of Information Request" and "Content Removal Request" documents (Documents 1-4, 28-73) reveals a pervasive effort by the AEC to flag and potentially censor online content. The consistent application of exemptions like "prejudice the conduct of an investigation of a breach, or possible breach, of the law" (Section 37(1)(a)) for these numerous requests effectively cloaks the specific content flagged and the reasons behind these government interventions. This suggests a desire to control public narratives rather than simply administer elections.

  2. Opaque "Methods" and "Procedures" of Influence: Numerous "Email - Meta" documents (e.g., 74-81) are entirely withheld under Section 37(2)(b) to "disclose lawful methods or procedures for preventing, detecting, investigating, or dealing with matters arising out of, breaches or evasions of the law the disclosure of which would... prejudice the effectiveness of those methods or procedures." This highly concerning exemption explicitly hides the how of government surveillance and potential content manipulation on private platforms, raising red flags about undisclosed tactics and overreach into online speech.

  3. Institutionalized Collaboration with Big Tech: The consistent stream of communications and scheduled meetings with Meta, Twitter/X Corp., Google/YouTube, and TikTok (e.g., "AEC Engagement for the Proposed Referendum," "TikTok AEC Agenda," "Google & YouTube Election Escalation Pathways") demonstrates a deeply embedded relationship between the AEC and these tech giants. The AEC actively seeks to "confirm continued referral processes" and discusses "recent or pending changes" on platforms (Document 169), indicating a proactive and adaptive approach to maintaining its influence over the digital information environment.

  4. "Trusted Flagger" Programs and Mission Creep: The AEC's keen interest in joining YouTube's "Trusted Flagger" program (Documents 100-113), specifically under "misinformation and hate speech verticals," is alarming. While the AEC publicly claims its role is limited to the "referendum process" and "does not have a role in fact-checking claims about the 'Yes' or 'No' campaigns" (Document 193A), its pursuit of "Trusted Flagger" status for broad categories like "hate speech" suggests a significant expansion of its self-assigned mandate into areas traditionally beyond electoral administration. The request for "whitelisting" multiple AEC email accounts (socialmedia@aec.gov.au, EIAT@aec.gov.au, authorisationsection@aec.gov.au) for direct access to platforms' "Safety Enforcement Tools" (Document 160) further solidifies concerns about an institutionalized content monitoring and referral apparatus.

  5. Questionable Effectiveness and Potential Waste: Document 171 reveals that, despite the AEC's "significant time processing" content referrals to Twitter/X Corp., "nil actions have been taken against any of the below." This raises serious questions about the efficiency and real-world impact of these extensive government efforts. Is this a case of bureaucratic inefficiency, or is it merely demonstrating the government's persistent attempts to control content, regardless of immediate success? The investment of public resources into a process yielding "nil actions" warrants further scrutiny.

  6. Lack of Transparency as Standard Operating Procedure: The sheer volume of "Release in part" or "Exempt" decisions, overwhelmingly justified by "personal privacy," "business affairs," "proper and efficient conduct of an agency," or "prejudice investigation/methods," creates a profound lack of transparency. This systematic withholding of information prevents the public from understanding the full scope, rationale, and outcomes of the government's collaboration with tech companies, fostering an environment where accountability is severely hindered.

In summary, these documents expose an Australian Electoral Commission that is not merely overseeing elections but is actively engaged in shaping online discourse, maintaining deep, often secret, relationships with tech companies, and doing so with a disturbing lack of transparency. The reliance on broad exemptions and vague justifications for withholding information underscores a government apparatus seemingly more concerned with controlling information flow than with open and accountable public service.

These FOI documents unequivocally demonstrate the government's unwavering commitment to effective governance, particularly in safeguarding the integrity of Australia's democratic processes. The records reveal the proactive and diligent efforts of the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) and the Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce (EIAT) in ensuring fair and accurate electoral events, including ongoing preparations for the proposed referendum and recent by-elections.

A key highlight is the government's robust engagement and collaborative partnerships with major digital platforms such as Twitter (now X), Meta, TikTok, and Google/YouTube. These strategic interactions are crucial for addressing the evolving challenges of the digital age, enabling the government to effectively manage online information, combat misinformation, and enforce electoral laws. The documents show ongoing dialogues, content referral processes, and the adoption of new tools like TikTok's Safety Enforcement Tool, all designed to maintain a clean and reliable information environment for the public.

While some documents are released in part or remain exempt, this reflects a judicious application of necessary regulations. Exemptions related to 'personal privacy' (Section 47F) underscore the government's dedication to protecting individual data. 'Substantial adverse effect on proper and efficient conduct of an agency' (Section 47E(d)) and 'prejudice the conduct of an investigation' (Section 37(1)(a), 37(2)(b)) are vital provisions that shield sensitive operational methods and ongoing legal inquiries, ensuring the government's continued ability to perform its duties effectively and uphold the rule of law. Furthermore, the protection of 'business affairs' (Section 47G(1)) and 'deliberative processes' (Section 47C(1)) ensures commercial confidentiality and allows for candid internal policy development, both contributing to sound governance.

Any instances of 'content removal requests' or 'investigations of a breach' are not controversies, but rather essential actions taken to uphold the integrity of our electoral system and ensure public confidence. These are challenges actively and responsibly managed by the government to protect the public from deceptive practices.

In essence, these documents provide compelling evidence of a government tirelessly working to serve the public interest, adapting to modern challenges, fostering vital industry partnerships, and upholding the highest standards of electoral integrity and information management for the benefit of all Australians.

These FOI documents reveal a government apparatus obsessed with control and shrouded in an alarming degree of opacity, actively collaborating with powerful tech platforms to manage public discourse under the guise of "electoral integrity." The sheer volume and nature of the exemptions applied are damning indicators of a systemic failure in transparency and a deliberate effort to shield government operations from public scrutiny.

A Deliberate Veil of Secrecy:
The most glaring sign of potential misconduct and incompetence is the pervasive use of exemptions, particularly those related to Section 47E(d) - substantial adverse effect on proper and efficient conduct of an agency, Section 37(1)(a) - prejudice the conduct of an investigation, and Section 37(2)(b) - disclose lawful methods or procedures... prejudice the effectiveness.

  • Concealed Operations: The frequent full exemption of documents under 47E(d) (e.g., Docs 1A, 2, 3, 7, 9, 9A) screams that the Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) and its Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce (EIAT) are engaged in activities they deem too sensitive or potentially embarrassing to disclose. The claim that revealing their "proper and efficient conduct" would be substantially harmed suggests either profound fragility in their operations or a cover-up of questionable practices.
  • Weaponizing "Investigation" for Opacity: The widespread application of Section 37(1)(a) to withhold information, especially regarding formal legal notices (s 321F Notice – Docs 4A, 129A), content removal requests (Docs 31-73), and Google interactions (Docs 88-99), implies an incessant state of "investigation" that conveniently keeps crucial details from the public. This is a thinly veiled excuse to avoid accountability for what constitutes a "breach" and how it's handled. The public is deliberately kept in the dark about the very legal mechanisms the AEC uses to influence online content.
  • Confessed Incompetence or Malice of Methods: The repeated use of Section 37(2)(b) for numerous Meta and Twitter emails (Docs 16-27, 74-81) is perhaps the most condemning revelation. The justification that disclosing the government's "lawful methods or procedures for preventing, detecting, investigating" breaches would "prejudice their effectiveness" strongly implies these methods are either so rudimentary, unreliable, or ethically dubious that their exposure would render them useless or expose them as unfit for purpose. This is a staggering admission of operational weakness, or worse, a deliberate choice to operate in secrecy because the methods themselves cannot withstand public scrutiny.

Prioritizing Corporate Secrecy over Public Right to Know:
The consistent application of Section 47G(1) - business affairs (e.g., Docs 4, 5, 136, 137, 151A, 153-162) and Section 47(1) - information with commercial value (Docs 169B, 169C) demonstrates a disturbing prioritization of private corporate interests over public transparency. Crucial documents like "AEC Escalation Channels 2023" and "Partner Support Portal Training Deck"—which would reveal the precise mechanics of government-platform collaboration on information control—are entirely withheld to protect the "commercial value" of tech giants. This suggests an uncomfortably close, potentially collusive relationship where government agencies facilitate corporate opacity in matters of public interest.

Aggressive Information Control and Narrative Shaping:
The documents reveal a proactive, not reactive, stance from the AEC in managing online narratives:

  • Active Content Removal: The sheer number of "Twitter Receipt of Content Removal Request" documents (Docs 31-73) confirms the AEC's extensive engagement in direct content removal efforts, extending beyond what might be considered "electoral fraud" to broader "misinformation."
  • Government as "Misinformation" Arbiters: Emails seeking "misinformation narratives" from Microsoft (Docs 141-146) and the AEC’s discussion about a "Referendum disinformation register" reveal the government's active role in defining and tracking what constitutes "disinformation." This encroaches dangerously close to state-sanctioned narrative control.
  • Formalized Censorship Channels: The adoption of "TikTok Safety Enforcement Tool (TSET)" (Docs 5, 156-159) and the AEC's eagerness to become "YouTube Trusted Flaggers" (Docs 100-113) demonstrate the establishment of formal, direct pathways for government agencies to flag and remove content. The AEC's keen interest in signing Non-Disclosure Agreements (NDAs) for the "Trusted Flagger" program (Docs 105-108, 110) further highlights the desire for absolute secrecy around these content policing activities.
  • Confirmed Failures and Lack of Enforcement: Despite these extensive efforts, document 171 directly admits to a shocking level of ineffectiveness: "Disappointingly, according to our records, nil actions have been taken against any of the below after significant time processing. As you would appreciate, the content of these referrals is of significant concern to us, particularly with regards to threats towards AEC staff, and mis/disinformation regarding electoral processes." This is a stark admission of failure, demonstrating that even with formal "referral pathways," the government's attempts to control online information are either fundamentally flawed or actively disregarded by the platforms. Yet, the AEC continues these efforts, begging the question of their true effectiveness or hidden agenda.

In conclusion, these documents paint a damning picture of a government agency (AEC) and its taskforce (EIAT) operating in extreme secrecy, prioritizing the "business affairs" of private tech companies, and actively engaging in extensive content monitoring and removal attempts—even when those attempts prove ineffective. The pervasive use of broad exemptions denies the public critical insight into how their information environment is being shaped, suggesting a profound lack of transparency, potential operational incompetence, and a deeply concerning expansion of state influence into free speech under the guise of "defending democracy."

Good afternoon 

,  

Recently, the Australian Parliament passed the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Amendment Act 2023 which 
amended the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Act 1984. The Referendum Act outlines the process for a federal 
referendum event and includes the role of the Australian Electoral Commission in the administration and 
operational delivery of a referendum.  

As outlined in the Referendum Act, the AEC is responsible for the administration of laws that deal with certain 
referendum communications, this includes some communications shared on social media platforms. The AEC is 
providing you with the attached letter outlining the current legislative environment and circumstances where the 
AEC may contact you concerning referendum related content. 

Further legislative updates:  

In addition to the recently passed Amendment Act, the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander 
Voice) 2023 Bill was also introduced to Parliament in late March. The bill has been referred to a Parliamentary 
Committee, due to report on 15 May 2023. Please note, the Bill has not yet passed Parliament, meaning the 
referendum is still proposed. Should the constitution alteration bill be passed, a referendum must be held no earlier 
than two months and no later than six months following the passing.  

While a date hasn’t been announced, the Government have stated their intent to hold the referendum sometime 
between September and December 2023. The exact timing is a matter for Government and the AEC is not provided 
with advanced notice. The date will be formalised by the issuing of a writ by the Governor-General, which is the 
formal instruction to the AEC to conduct a poll. 

AEC Information campaign launched: 

In April, the AEC launched our referendum information campaign. This initial stage of the campaign is centred 
around ‘early-education’ providing information to educate voters on federal referendums. Please see our media 
release available here.  

As we move through the referendum timeline in the coming months, our campaigns will continue to gradually 
change focuses, including topics such as enrolment and voter services (how/where voters can cast their vote).  

Throughout the campaign, the AEC will be engaging in digital advertising and media outreach, as well as working 
with community groups and other stakeholders, to educate voters on referendums. The AEC will be directing voters 
towards our dedicated referendum sub-site at https://www.aec.gov.au/referendums/ for further information.  

We will look to keep you updated with key milestones as our communication campaign progresses.  

1

s 47Fs 47Fs 47Fs 47F


--- Page 2 ---

Referendum resources: 

As part of the campaign, we have also launched a number of referendum resources, including our Referendum 
disinformation register, which will list prominent pieces of disinformation relating to the referendum process, the 
correct information, and any action taken by the AEC. Importantly, the disinformation register focuses solely on mis 
and disinformation about the referendum process. The AEC does not have a role in fact-checking claims about the 
'Yes' or 'No' campaigns for the referendum, though we are responsible for distribution of a ‘yes/no’ pamphlet to 
each household where there is an enrolled voter. Content for the booklet is provided by parliamentarians 
representing each side, and published verbatim by the AEC. 

The AEC has also made available a number of Electoral backgrounders. These backgrounders communicate 
referendum and electoral law, particularly in relation to referendum and electoral offences, in relatively plain 
English for the information and guidance of interested persons. These backgrounders are not intended to substitute 
a careful reading of the legislation. Rather, they are published for general information only and should not be relied 
upon for any particular purpose.  

I would encourage you all to familiarise yourself with the information on our referendum sub-site, and of course, if 
you have any questions, please don’t hesitate to contact us at EIAT@aec.gov.au.  

We will soon be in contact to discuss suitable times for a meeting with the Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce.  

Kind regards,  

 | Director  

Defending Democracy Unit | Electoral Integrity and Communications Branch 
Australian Electoral Commission

Regarding formal campaign periods, there is no limit in the Commonwealth Electoral Act 1918 regarding the 
amount, the format or the timing of electoral communication. However, campaigning generally occurs between the 
issue of the writs and voting day. For the Aston by-election this will be Monday 27 February to Saturday 1 April.  
Other important dates to consider are the ’Close of Nominations’ which has been announced as midday Thursday 09 
March 2023 and the ‘Declaration of Nominations’ Friday 10 March 2023. By this point no further candidates will be 
able to nominate.

Good afternoon 

,  

Recently, the Australian Parliament passed the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Amendment Act 2023 which 
amended the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Act 1984. The Referendum Act outlines the process for a federal 
referendum event and includes the role of the Australian Electoral Commission in the administration and 
operational delivery of a referendum.  

As outlined in the Referendum Act, the AEC is responsible for the administration of laws that deal with certain 
referendum communications, this includes some communications shared on social media platforms. The AEC is 
providing you with the attached letter outlining the current legislative environment and circumstances where the 
AEC may contact you concerning referendum related content. 

Further legislative updates:  

In addition to the recently passed Amendment Act, the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander 
Voice) 2023 Bill was also introduced to Parliament in late March. The bill has been referred to a Parliamentary 
Committee, due to report on 15 May 2023. Please note, the Bill has not yet passed Parliament, meaning the 
referendum is still proposed. Should the constitution alteration bill be passed, a referendum must be held no earlier 
than two months and no later than six months following the passing.  

While a date hasn’t been announced, the Government have stated their intent to hold the referendum sometime 
between September and December 2023. The exact timing is a matter for Government and the AEC is not provided 
with advanced notice. The date will be formalised by the issuing of a writ by the Governor-General, which is the 
formal instruction to the AEC to conduct a poll. 

AEC Information campaign launched: 

In April, the AEC launched our referendum information campaign. This initial stage of the campaign is centred 
around ‘early-education’ providing information to educate voters on federal referendums. Please see our media 
release available here.  

As we move through the referendum timeline in the coming months, our campaigns will continue to gradually 
change focuses, including topics such as enrolment and voter services (how/where voters can cast their vote).  

Throughout the campaign, the AEC will be engaging in digital advertising and media outreach, as well as working 
with community groups and other stakeholders, to educate voters on referendums. The AEC will be directing voters 
towards our dedicated referendum sub-site at https://www.aec.gov.au/referendums/ for further information.  

We will look to keep you updated with key milestones as our communication campaign progresses.  

1

s 47Fs 47Fs 47Fs 47F


--- Page 2 ---

Referendum resources: 

As part of the campaign, we have also launched a number of referendum resources, including our Referendum 
disinformation register, which will list prominent pieces of disinformation relating to the referendum process, the 
correct information, and any action taken by the AEC. Importantly, the disinformation register focuses solely on mis 
and disinformation about the referendum process. The AEC does not have a role in fact-checking claims about the 
'Yes' or 'No' campaigns for the referendum, though we are responsible for distribution of a ‘yes/no’ pamphlet to 
each household where there is an enrolled voter. Content for the booklet is provided by parliamentarians 
representing each side, and published verbatim by the AEC. 

The AEC has also made available a number of Electoral backgrounders. These backgrounders communicate 
referendum and electoral law, particularly in relation to referendum and electoral offences, in relatively plain 
English for the information and guidance of interested persons. These backgrounders are not intended to substitute 
a careful reading of the legislation. Rather, they are published for general information only and should not be relied 
upon for any particular purpose.  

I would encourage you all to familiarise yourself with the information on our referendum sub-site, and of course, if 
you have any questions, please don’t hesitate to contact us at EIAT@aec.gov.au.  

We will soon be in contact to discuss suitable times for a meeting with the Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce.  

Kind regards,  

 | Director  

Defending Democracy Unit | Electoral Integrity and Communications Branch 
Australian Electoral Commission

AEC Information campaign launched: 

In April, the AEC launched our referendum information campaign. This initial stage of the campaign is centred 
around ‘early-education’ providing information to educate voters on federal referendums. Please see our media 
release available here.  

As we move through the referendum timeline in the coming months, our campaigns will continue to gradually 
change focuses, including topics such as enrolment and voter services (how/where voters can cast their vote).  

Throughout the campaign, the AEC will be engaging in digital advertising and media outreach, as well as working 
with community groups and other stakeholders, to educate voters on referendums. The AEC will be directing voters 
towards our dedicated referendum sub-site at https://www.aec.gov.au/referendums/ for further information.  

We will look to keep you updated with key milestones as our communication campaign progresses.  

Referendum resources: 

As part of the campaign, we have also launched a number of referendum resources, including our Referendum 
disinformation register, which will list prominent pieces of disinformation relating to the referendum process, the 
correct information, and any action taken by the AEC. Importantly, the disinformation register focuses solely on mis 
and disinformation about the referendum process. The AEC does not have a role in fact-checking claims about the 
'Yes' or 'No' campaigns for the referendum, though we are responsible for distribution of a ‘yes/no’ pamphlet to 
each household where there is an enrolled voter. Content for the booklet is provided by parliamentarians 
representing each side, and published verbatim by the AEC. 

The AEC has also made available a number of Electoral backgrounders. These backgrounders communicate 
referendum and electoral law, particularly in relation to referendum and electoral offences, in relatively plain 
English for the information and guidance of interested persons. These backgrounders are not intended to substitute 
a careful reading of the legislation. Rather, they are published for general information only and should not be relied 
upon for any particular purpose.  

I would encourage you all to familiarise yourself with the information on our referendum sub-site, and of course, if 
you have any questions, please don’t hesitate to contact us at EIAT@aec.gov.au.  

We will soon be in contact to discuss suitable times for a meeting with the Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce.  

Kind regards,  

 | Director  

Defending Democracy Unit | Electoral Integrity and Communications Branch 

Australian Electoral Commission

Afternoon 
Hope you are going along well! Winter has well and truly hit here in Canberra, so I’m about ready to move to warmer locations
already!
By way of quick update, Mr Rogers and Mr Haigh appeared before a Senate Finance and Public Administration Committee hearing
on 4 May down in Melbourne, where they were asked about the engagement with online platforms including yourselves. I
understand the response referenced that we had met, that had been provided with additional escalation points for Twitter
referrals and that he was broadly comfortable with cooperation across platforms at this time. We are currently in preparations to
support Mr Rogers in his appearance at Senate Estimates in the week commencing Mon 22 May.
Looking to also follow up on our use of the new referrals process via the legal portal provided. Please see below for a list of the
posts referred to Twitter, as of middle of the day today, 15 May. We have removed previously reviewed/escalated/resolved items
outlined in our past correspondence for brevity. Disappointingly, according to our records, nil actions have been taken against any
of the below after significant time processing. As you would appreciate, the content of these referrals is of significant concern to
us, particularly with regards to threats towards AEC staff, and mis/disinformation regarding electoral processes.
For your background, the three highlighted referrals were originally made via the platform public channels (previous process),
then referred again via the legal portal when we switched over, as per your instructions. The other referrals were all made directly
via the legal portal. I am seeking to escalate the review of these referrals and re-open discussion more broadly on expectations
when using this channel. Please also let me know if there is different information we should be including or highlighting, or if there
are other ways that we can improve our requests.
I understand that you also received my email that provided a letter from our Regulatory Law team, and some additional
information that we hope will be of assistance to you in the lead up to the proposed referendum. If there are any questions
coming out of this, please do not hesitate to get in touch.
Many thanks,

Good afternoon 
Greetings from what is turning into a disappointingly short summer in Canberra!
The Australian Electoral Commission is interested in scheduling an initial meeting with Twitter to build
on the productive collaboration we had during 2022 and to highlight the change in scope between the
federal election and the proposed referendum which could take place later this year. I understand
that you must be getting contacted from multiple directions at present within Australian government,
however hopefully we can work here to consolidate at least some of that thematically for you over
the coming months.
In terms of agenda – we’re eager to hear about any recent or pending changes to Twitter that may be
of significance to an electoral and/or referendum event. Similarly, we’ll provide an overview of our
preliminary plans to ensure referendum integrity through engagement with the Electoral Integrity
Assurance Taskforce (EIAT) and discuss elements of our communications and public engagement
strategy. Of course, we’ll seek to re-establish the appropriate enquiry and/or referral lines for
electoral issues that may arise on your platform.
As you would be aware, the AEC chairs the EIAT – a cross-Government cooperation between agencies
on matters relating to electoral integrity – and we would look to hold future meetings between
Twitter and representatives of Taskforce agencies as plans for the proposed referendum fall into
place.
If you could advise, at your earliest convenience, a preferred representative/s from Twitter to attend
these meetings, that would be much appreciated. We’ll then seek to confirm an appropriate time to
schedule a Teams meeting.
We of course note that Twitter is undergoing significant change at present and appreciate the
opportunity to confirm our continued engagement and collaboration, in support of maintaining
accurate electoral and referendum information.
Kind regards

 | Director

Defending Democracy Unit | Electoral Integrity and Communications Branch
Australian Electoral Commission

Proposed Referendum Update: Referral of Content from the AEC [SEC=OFFICIAL]
Tuesday, 9 May 2023 3:17:59 PM
image001.gif
image002.gif
Twitter Letter - Referral of Content from the AEC.pdf

Good afternoon 
Recently, the Australian Parliament passed the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Amendment Act
2023 which amended the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Act 1984. The Referendum Act outlines
the process for a federal referendum event and includes the role of the Australian Electoral
Commission in the administration and operational delivery of a referendum.
As outlined in the Referendum Act, the AEC is responsible for the administration of laws that deal with
certain referendum communications, this includes some communications shared on social media
platforms. The AEC is providing you with the attached letter outlining the current legislative
environment and circumstances where the AEC may contact you concerning referendum related
content.
Further legislative updates:
In addition to the recently passed Amendment Act, the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginal and Torres
Strait Islander Voice) 2023 Bill was also introduced to Parliament in late March. The bill has been
referred to a Parliamentary Committee, due to report on 15 May 2023. Please note, the Bill has not
yet passed Parliament, meaning the referendum is still proposed. Should the constitution alteration
bill be passed, a referendum must be held no earlier than two months and no later than six months
following the passing.
While a date hasn’t been announced, the Government have stated their intent to hold the
referendum sometime between September and December 2023. The exact timing is a matter for
Government and the AEC is not provided with advanced notice. The date will be formalised by the
issuing of a writ by the Governor-General, which is the formal instruction to the AEC to conduct a poll.
AEC Information campaign launched:
In April, the AEC launched our referendum information campaign. This initial stage of the campaign is
centred around ‘early-education’ providing information to educate voters on federal referendums.
Please see our media release available here.
As we move through the referendum timeline in the coming months, our campaigns will continue to
gradually change focuses, including topics such as enrolment and voter services (how/where voters
can cast their vote).
Throughout the campaign, the AEC will be engaging in digital advertising and media outreach, as well
as working with community groups and other stakeholders, to educate voters on referendums. The
AEC will be directing voters towards our dedicated referendum sub-site at
https://www.aec.gov.au/referendums/ for further information.
We will look to keep you updated with key milestones as our communication campaign progresses.
Referendum resources:
As part of the campaign, we have also launched a number of referendum resources, including our
Referendum disinformation register, which will list prominent pieces of disinformation relating to the
referendum process, the correct information, and any action taken by the AEC. Importantly, the
disinformation register focuses solely on mis and disinformation about the referendum process.
The AEC does not have a role in fact-checking claims about the 'Yes' or 'No' campaigns for the
referendum, though we are responsible for distribution of a ‘yes/no’ pamphlet to each household
where there is an enrolled voter. Content for the booklet is provided by parliamentarians
representing each side, and published verbatim by the AEC.
The AEC has also made available a number of Electoral backgrounders. These backgrounders
communicate referendum and electoral law, particularly in relation to referendum and electoral
offences, in relatively plain English for the information and guidance of interested persons. These

Section 47fSection 47f


--- Page 2 ---

backgrounders are not intended to substitute a careful reading of the legislation. Rather, they are
published for general information only and should not be relied upon for any particular purpose.
I would encourage you all to familiarise yourself with the information on our referendum sub-site, and
of course, if you have any questions, please don’t hesitate to contact us at EIAT@aec.gov.au.
We will soon be in contact to discuss suitable times for a meeting with the Electoral Integrity
Assurance Taskforce.
Kind regards,

 | Director

Defending Democracy Unit | Electoral Integrity and Communications Branch
Australian Electoral Commission

On Tue, May 9, 2023 at 2:17 PM EIAT <EIAT@aec.gov.au> wrote:

Good afternoon 

Recently, the Australian Parliament passed the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Amendment Act 2023
which amended the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Act 1984. The Referendum Act outlines the process
for a federal referendum event and includes the role of the Australian Electoral Commission in the
administration and operational delivery of a referendum.

As outlined in the Referendum Act, the AEC is responsible for the administration of laws that deal with certain
referendum communications, this includes some communications shared on social media platforms. The AEC
is providing you with the attached letter outlining the current legislative environment and circumstances where
the AEC may contact you concerning referendum related content.

Further legislative updates:

In addition to the recently passed Amendment Act, the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginal and Torres Strait
Islander Voice) 2023 Bill was also introduced to Parliament in late March. The bill has been referred to a
Parliamentary Committee, due to report on 15 May 2023. Please note, the Bill has not yet passed
Parliament, meaning the referendum is still proposed. Should the constitution alteration bill be passed, a
referendum must be held no earlier than two months and no later than six months following the passing.

While a date hasn’t been announced, the Government have stated their intent to hold the referendum sometime
between September and December 2023. The exact timing is a matter for Government and the AEC is not
provided with advanced notice. The date will be formalised by the issuing of a writ by the Governor-General,
which is the formal instruction to the AEC to conduct a poll.

AEC Information campaign launched:

In April, the AEC launched our referendum information campaign. This initial stage of the campaign is
centred around ‘early-education’ providing information to educate voters on federal referendums. Please see
our media release available here.

As we move through the referendum timeline in the coming months, our campaigns will continue to gradually
change focuses, including topics such as enrolment and voter services (how/where voters can cast their vote).

Throughout the campaign, the AEC will be engaging in digital advertising and media outreach, as well as
working with community groups and other stakeholders, to educate voters on referendums. The AEC will be
directing voters towards our dedicated referendum sub-site at https://www.aec.gov.au/referendums/ for further
information.

We will look to keep you updated with key milestones as our communication campaign progresses.

Referendum resources:

As part of the campaign, we have also launched a number of referendum resources, including our Referendum
disinformation register, which will list prominent pieces of disinformation relating to the referendum process,
the correct information, and any action taken by the AEC. Importantly, the disinformation register focuses
solely on mis and disinformation about the referendum process. The AEC does not have a role in fact-

Good afternoon, 

I'm writing to let you know that the Australian Electoral Commission has been successfully on-boarded onto 
TikTok's Safety Enforcement Tool (TSET). 

TSET is TikTok's secure web portal designed to enable our Government partners to easily submit and review 
content takedown requests. Going forward, you can submit requests through the TSET portal rather than using the 
 email address. This will enable you to easily track the progress of your agency's ongoing and 

completed requests, and provides you with direct access to our dedicated Trust & Safety teams.

Good afternoon 

Recently, the Australian Parliament passed the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Amendment Act 2023 which 
amended the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Act 1984. The Referendum Act outlines the process for a federal 
referendum event and includes the role of the Australian Electoral Commission in the administration and 
operational delivery of a referendum.  

As outlined in the Referendum Act, the AEC is responsible for the administration of laws that deal with certain 
referendum communications, this includes some communications shared on social media platforms. The AEC is 
providing you with the attached letter outlining the current legislative environment and circumstances where the 
AEC may contact you concerning referendum related content. 

Further legislative updates:  

In addition to the recently passed Amendment Act, the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander 
Voice) 2023 Bill was also introduced to Parliament in late March. The bill has been referred to a Parliamentary 
Committee, due to report on 15 May 2023. Please note, the Bill has not yet passed Parliament, meaning the 
referendum is still proposed. Should the constitution alteration bill be passed, a referendum must be held no earlier 
than two months and no later than six months following the passing.  

While a date hasn’t been announced, the Government have stated their intent to hold the referendum sometime 
between September and December 2023. The exact timing is a matter for Government and the AEC is not provided 
with advanced notice. The date will be formalised by the issuing of a writ by the Governor‐General, which is the 
formal instruction to the AEC to conduct a poll. 

AEC Information campaign launched: 

In April, the AEC launched our referendum information campaign. This initial stage of the campaign is centred 
around ‘early‐education’ providing information to educate voters on federal referendums. Please see our media 
release available here.  

As we move through the referendum timeline in the coming months, our campaigns will continue to gradually 
change focuses, including topics such as enrolment and voter services (how/where voters can cast their vote).  

Throughout the campaign, the AEC will be engaging in digital advertising and media outreach, as well as working 
with community groups and other stakeholders, to educate voters on referendums. The AEC will be directing voters 
towards our dedicated referendum sub‐site at https://www.aec.gov.au/referendums/ for further information.  

We will look to keep you updated with key milestones as our communication campaign progresses.

Referendum resources: 

As part of the campaign, we have also launched a number of referendum resources, including our Referendum 
disinformation register, which will list prominent pieces of disinformation relating to the referendum process, the 
correct information, and any action taken by the AEC. Importantly, the disinformation register focuses solely on mis 
and disinformation about the referendum process. The AEC does not have a role in fact‐checking claims about the 
'Yes' or 'No' campaigns for the referendum, though we are responsible for distribution of a ‘yes/no’ pamphlet to 
each household where there is an enrolled voter. Content for the booklet is provided by parliamentarians 
representing each side, and published verbatim by the AEC. 

The AEC has also made available a number of Electoral backgrounders. These backgrounders communicate 
referendum and electoral law, particularly in relation to referendum and electoral offences, in relatively plain 
English for the information and guidance of interested persons. These backgrounders are not intended to substitute 
a careful reading of the legislation. Rather, they are published for general information only and should not be relied 
upon for any particular purpose.  

I would encourage you all to familiarise yourself with the information on our referendum sub‐site, and of course, if 
you have any questions, please don’t hesitate to contact us at EIAT@aec.gov.au.  

We will soon be in contact to discuss suitable times for a meeting with the Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce.  

Kind regards,  

 | Director  

Defending Democracy Unit | Electoral Integrity and Communications Branch 
Australian Electoral Commission

the recent federal election, the AEC are interested in scheduling an initial meeting with Google to highlight the 
change in scope between these two events.

If you could advise, if this window would suit yourselves and/or other Google representatives, I’ll make 
arrangements for a Microsoft Teams meeting. Of course, very glad to discuss alternative times if the above option 
don’t suits. Should you happen to be in Canberra and available, you would of course be welcome to join us here at 
the National Office for the meeting.

Hi 

Great to see you yesterday and hear more from the AEC about plans for the upcoming referendum. Please see 
attached escalation paths (which applied to the election last year and will also apply to the referendum). You'll see 
that slide 2 includes both email addresses and Hannah's phone number for emergency / out of hours issues. 

Here is a website with more information about the Advanced Protection Program, which is offered to individuals at 
high risk of being targeted by bad actors; please note that these tools can only be used across Google services 
(Gmail, Drive etc). So they are really only relevant for people who are using these services for sharing sensitive 
information (which would be worthy of being targeted). We talk about this program in our civics training, which is 
delivered to political parties as well as individual elected representatives who take us up on the offer of training. 

Finally, I promised to send through more information about our AI announcements last week. The blog post links off 
to a number of other resources that should hopefully answer any questions you have. I will note that all Google 
employees have today been given access to Bard and therefore we will start testing it locally in the context of 
referendum questions and start providing feedback. We'll keep you posted when we have a clearer sense of when 
Bard might be made more widely available. 

Kind regards

Today Google has announced that referendum related advertising is being scoped into our political ads policy, 
meaning anyone running referendum related advertising will need to have their advertising account/s verified, and 
their ads will appear in our political ads transparency report.  

Also wanted to check in if any resources regarding the below might be available as yet? We did see the launch of the 
new disinfo register and have already passed it on to our Trust and Safety colleagues as one of the authoritative 
sources they should rely on for the purpose of applying our election misinformation policy.  

From our end, I can confirm that the AEC will; 

1.  Providing you with a letter outlining the regularly environment once legislation has passed Parliament. This 

letter will provide you with the most accurate information concerning the referendum process. 

2.  Provide updates on our referendum education resources as they are made available. This will include a 

number of videos and a referendum specific Disinformation Register (please find a link to the 2022 Federal 
Election register here). Once live, the Register will be regularly updated with common pieces of 
disinformation we are encountering. 

Cheers,

On Tue, May 9, 2023 at 2:42 PM EIAT <EIAT@aec.gov.au> wrote: 

Good afternoon 

Recently, the Australian Parliament passed the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Amendment Act 2023 which 
amended the Referendum (Machinery Provisions) Act 1984. The Referendum Act outlines the process for a federal 
referendum event and includes the role of the Australian Electoral Commission in the administration and 
operational delivery of a referendum.  

As outlined in the Referendum Act, the AEC is responsible for the administration of laws that deal with certain 
referendum communications, this includes some communications shared on social media platforms. The AEC is 

1

Section 47FSection 47FSection 47FSection 47FSection 47FSection 47FSection 47FSection 47FSection 47F


--- Page 2 ---

providing you with the attached letter outlining the current legislative environment and circumstances where the 
AEC may contact you concerning referendum related content. 

Further legislative updates:  

In addition to the recently passed Amendment Act, the Constitution Alteration (Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander 
Voice) 2023 Bill was also introduced to Parliament in late March. The bill has been referred to a Parliamentary 
Committee, due to report on 15 May 2023. Please note, the Bill has not yet passed Parliament, meaning the 
referendum is still proposed. Should the constitution alteration bill be passed, a referendum must be held no 
earlier than two months and no later than six months following the passing.  

While a date hasn’t been announced, the Government have stated their intent to hold the referendum sometime 
between September and December 2023. The exact timing is a matter for Government and the AEC is not provided 
with advanced notice. The date will be formalised by the issuing of a writ by the Governor‐General, which is the 
formal instruction to the AEC to conduct a poll. 

AEC Information campaign launched: 

In April, the AEC launched our referendum information campaign. This initial stage of the campaign is centred 
around ‘early‐education’ providing information to educate voters on federal referendums. Please see our media 
release available here.  

As we move through the referendum timeline in the coming months, our campaigns will continue to gradually 
change focuses, including topics such as enrolment and voter services (how/where voters can cast their vote).  

Throughout the campaign, the AEC will be engaging in digital advertising and media outreach, as well as working 
with community groups and other stakeholders, to educate voters on referendums. The AEC will be directing voters 
towards our dedicated referendum sub‐site at https://www.aec.gov.au/referendums/ for further information.  

We will look to keep you updated with key milestones as our communication campaign progresses.  

Referendum resources: 

As part of the campaign, we have also launched a number of referendum resources, including our Referendum 
disinformation register, which will list prominent pieces of disinformation relating to the referendum process, the 
correct information, and any action taken by the AEC. Importantly, the disinformation register focuses solely on 
mis and disinformation about the referendum process. The AEC does not have a role in fact‐checking claims about 
the 'Yes' or 'No' campaigns for the referendum, though we are responsible for distribution of a ‘yes/no’ pamphlet 
to each household where there is an enrolled voter. Content for the booklet is provided by parliamentarians 
representing each side, and published verbatim by the AEC. 

The AEC has also made available a number of Electoral backgrounders. These backgrounders communicate 
referendum and electoral law, particularly in relation to referendum and electoral offences, in relatively plain 
English for the information and guidance of interested persons. These backgrounders are not intended to 
substitute a careful reading of the legislation. Rather, they are published for general information only and should 
not be relied upon for any particular purpose.  

I would encourage you all to familiarise yourself with the information on our referendum sub‐site, and of course, if 
you have any questions, please don’t hesitate to contact us at EIAT@aec.gov.au.  

We will soon be in contact to discuss suitable times for a meeting with the Electoral Integrity Assurance Taskforce.  

Kind regards,
